{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7f4e299a-4d52-403c-ab64-021f425c0bb6","content":"Here's how to configure `.vscode/mcp.json` for a C# stdio MCP server:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Place this file at **`.vscode/mcp.json`** in your workspace root.\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace `command`/`args` with the path to the executable.\n- If your server uses **SSE** transport, use `\"type\": \"sse\"` with a `\"url\"` field instead.\n\nAfter saving, VS Code will detect the server automatically in agent mode — your tools should appear in the Copilot chat tool list.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e9053054-3fbf-441c-8e52-6df7524cb0d0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet. The user said they built it, but it's not in the current directory. That's fine — they're asking how to configure `mcp.json`, not asking me to build the server. I'll give them the configuration guidance.","outputTokens":314},"id":"ef45edf1-c551-4553-a0fa-445b3fd4f182","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:02:36.498Z","parentId":"c3b17581-c803-4fa3-95ad-0eff6e19e290"}
